would have to ask the House <lb/>
or its approval of a detailed <lb/>
statement of how this money was <lb/>
spent. The sum of $10,000 was also <lb/>
asked for to provide for the payment <lb/>
of one-half of the sessional indemnity <lb/>
and travelling expenses of the Mem-<lb break="maybe"/>oers. Both items were passed without <lb/>
discussion. <lb/></p> 

<p>OTTAWA GOVERNMENT RESPONSIBLE. <lb/></p> 

<p>In moving that when the House ad<lb break="no"/>journs to-morrow it do stand adjourn<lb break="no"/>ed until 8th June, the Premier said it <lb/>
was not necessary to enter into any <lb/>
lengthy explanation of the reasons for <lb/>
taking this step. The position breifly <lb/>
was that the North-West Government <lb/>
had not been made aware of the <lb/>
amount of money which is to be placed <lb/>
at the disposal of the Territories. Re<lb break="no"/>presentations had been made to Ottawa <lb/>
out up to the present time no action <lb/>
had been taken, at least officially, and <lb/>
communicated to the Legislature. On <lb/>
the morning after the Assembly met <lb/>
he had received an unofficial telegram <lb/>
from a member of the Ottawa Govern<lb break="no"/>ment informing him in general terms <lb/>
of the vote which is to be brought <lb/>
down. He was asked to consider the <lb/>
telegram as unofficical. The terms in<lb break="no"/>dicated in this telegram were not in <lb/>
the opinion of the local Government at <lb/>
